Pr0c5ViPY9XZpboV_01_ARzki2o ]: Toucan is coming to Celo.
Toucan connects the voluntary carbon market to web3 through the Toucan Brid=
ge, which tokenizes real-world carbon credits in exchange for semi-fungible=
 Tokenized CO2 (TCO2) tokens. With the credits on-chain, they create a tran=
sparent meta-registry and pools of Base Carbon Tonne (BCT) and Nature Carbo=
n Tonne (NCT) tokens to increase liquidity. As it says on its homepage, Tou=
can =E2=80=9Cbrings programmable carbon to web3.=E2=80=9D
After initially launching on Polygon and getting traction for its BCT token=
 via KlimaDAO, Toucan decided to go multi-chain and add Celo support in par=
tnership with the Celo Foundation and the Climate Collective. The Toucan te=
am laid out three reasons for adding Celo:=C2=A0
A supply of high-quality environmental assets
Infrastructure for planet-positive innovation
Capital and support to scale climate action in Web3
First, they=E2=80=99ll bridge BCT and NCT to Celo via the Curve Celo-Polygo=
n bridge. Then, they=E2=80=99ll deploy the full protocol on Celo. They also=
 plan to submit a governance proposal to the Celo Community for the Celo Re=
serve to accept BCT and NCT.=C2=A0
Toucan=E2=80=99s decision is validation of Celo=E2=80=99s strategy in a cou=
ple of different ways:=C2=A0
The Home for ReFi. Toucan added Celo next because that=E2=80=99s where the =
projects that are creating high-quality environmental assets to tokenize ar=
e.=C2=A0
Celo Reserve. By committing to back the Reserve with 40% natural capital ba=
cked assets, Celo is attracting projects creating those assets by essential=
ly raising their hand and saying they have a bid for all high-quality asset=
s.=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s also a point for the argument that web3 will be multi-chain, a=
nd any ReFi project will need to at least have a presence on Celo.=C2=A0
Flow Carbon
Another project working to tokenize carbon credits is Flowcarbon [ https://=
email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFUEGOhCAQfM1wNIDi4IHDXvYbpoHGIYtgsF3j75cZD5t0qp=
OuVKqrHBAupV5mKzuxN8x0bWgynntCIqzs2LHO0RsxSt2rYWLeDF5opVnc51ARV4jJUD2QbYdN0=
QHFkj8KzqViL8N7Z4OFUQfNp1FxtD146YIYB7Qw8NsXDh8xOzT4i_UqGVkyL6Jtf_RfD_nd5jzP=
LqRyOqi25M6VtR3BloNYNJJLyQephFSa867vhhGEDSCmYPUTwD0Gvi6y2w-7E7ift5xVkwvZUmN=
eGv3zghXTh2hJ5rbXI0e6ZsxgE_o7JN1dfWLPC2asrUM_A7WGFNeTaMDFeIdqLSj5lM_2HGvOvj=
RV_jf9AwX7gis ]. It=E2=80=99s creating the GNT token, backed by corporate-g=
rade carbon credits it brings on-chain, and also providing the infrastructu=
re to help corporations and individuals offset their emissions.=C2=A0
When I asked Flowcarbon=E2=80=99s Phil Fogel [ https://email.mg2.substack.c=
om/c/eJxFUM2OhCAMfprhaABFmQOHvex534AUqEpGwWDdiW-_OB42ado0zdfvxwPhlMtptrwTu5=
qlc0OT8L0vSISFHTsWG4MRvdSt6p4smC4IrTSLux0L4gpxMVQOZNvhluiBYk4fBOdSsdl06Fsh_=
TDwvusVoOajACcG14IXQbQ3LxwhYvJo8BfLmROyxcxE2_5ovx7yuxa946Wo8Xmt288clzFPLBrJ=
peSdVEIqzXnTNl0Pwo0gnqPTA4B_dHydZLMfbifwr-sBKyZlcrnENNXza4YVl8-hmrB1rkeKdFp=
M4BYMtz-6Y_o4thMmLDW-YIFqOIrrp6iNi_72UwNQcpBDFccqc8gVlf5J_wChJn-U ] why the=
y chose to build on Celo, he told me that they looked at all of the L1s and=
 L2s you=E2=80=99d expect, but that they chose Celo, which he called =E2=80=
=9Cthe OG,=E2=80=9D as home base for a few reasons:=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s a Proof-of-Stake chain, which ruled out Ethereum for now.=C2=
=A0
It=E2=80=99s carbon-neutral in both practice and ethos.
Low transaction fees were crucial because wrapping tokens would get expensi=
ve with high gas.
Potential liquidity support through the Celo Reserve and other initiatives=
=C2=A0
He also said that Celo is the most likely place a community ecosystem would=
 pop up, and that the people in the Celo ecosystem are =E2=80=9Cthe nicest,=
 most mission-driven people=E2=80=9D in the space.=C2=A0
Another check for the argument that, as long as the technical infrastructur=
e passes the test, a focused and mission-aligned community can be a strong =
competitive advantage for an L1.=C2=A0
Loam
While Toucan and Flowcarbon tokenizer carbon credits, Loam [ https://email.=
mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFUEtuxCAMPc2wjMCBhFmw6KbXQAacDGoCEZBWuX3pZFHJsi1Zz-_j=
sdGay2WOXBv7a7ZdB5lEP3Wj1qiws1KxMRgxgR6VfLJgZBBaaRarXQrRjnEzrZzEjtNt0WOLOb0=
RnINiLyMkAOch0EguOJjEIhc1-jBruQDBePPiGSIlT4a-qVw5EdvMq7WjPsaPB3z22jLuA659Y9=
EA708lKAFKcz6Mg5xQuAXFc3F6RvQPyfcVhnq62tB_DT7vrJiUm8slprWfv1640_Y-dOW2z_1Ms=
V2WErqNwm2q3dm8bdqVEpWeWbDYeiKK66fojYvpNtFdK5hh7uJYZw65o9I_6S-4DHsj ]=E2=80=
=99s plan is to actually =E2=80=9Cdeposit carbon back into Mother Earth=E2=
=80=9D and earn new offsets in the process.=C2=A0
Founded by Birju Shah and Ravi Yenduri, Loam=E2=80=99s vision is to create =
a marketplace for farming data, a fast, easy, and transparent platform to i=
ncentivize farmers to engage in regenerative practices. As Ravi describes i=
s, they want to create =E2=80=9Cchange today that pays off in the long-term=
=2E=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
That=E2=80=99s a financing trick, exactly what ReFi is designed for. There =
are all sorts of things that farmers can do to capture and sequester carbon=
, or release less in the first place, for which they might receive offsets =
a few years out, which they=E2=80=99d then have to sell. Loam will make it =
easy to finance those changes upfront, by selling the future credits to com=
panies that want to offset, to investors, or into pools on something like T=
oucan or Flowcarbon.=C2=A0
To Ravi, the decision to build on Celo was simple: =E2=80=9CThey have a mis=
sion. Other chains don=E2=80=99t have a mission. Farmers ask why we=E2=80=
=99re doing something, and we asked the same thing.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Plus, Celo Reserve is a significant potential buyer of the credits that Loa=
m produces, something that other chains can=E2=80=99t offer sustainably.=C2=
=A0
Once again, it comes down to mission and Celo=E2=80=99s early commitment. T=
he more Loams and Toucans and Vanas those things matter to, the more inevit=
able it will become that the next important ReFi project builds on Celo, un=
til it=E2=80=99s the default.
Each of these projects on its own is compelling, but appropriately, I think=
 Celo=E2=80=99s power, and the power of the ReFi ecosystem more broadly, is=
 how they all fit together.=C2=A0
Flori Ventures co-founder and GP Tomer Bariach, an active investor in the e=
cosystem, described it as a =E2=80=9Chuman and technological puzzle=E2=80=
=9D:=C2=A0
The projects who are winning in crypto are the ones who understand interope=
rability very quickly. This isn=E2=80=99t Apple vs. Microsoft. It=E2=80=99s=
 a world where everyone is building different pieces of the puzzle and coll=
aborating, increasing each others=E2=80=99 chances of success. The communit=
y is working on all angles =E2=80=93 futures, land, assessments, new carbon=
 credits, new categories for offsetting like biodiversity. If people see pi=
eces missing, they pull other people in to build this missing pieces. Findi=
ng a community of people that keep on bringing in more pieces is beautiful.=
=C2=A0
Talking to Tomer, it struck me that the Celo community of builders itself w=
as regenerative, each piece serving a unique purpose, each connected to the=
 larger whole.=C2=A0
And talking to Ed at Allegory, it struck me how prescient Celo=E2=80=99s fo=
cus on emerging markets was, how important a piece that is to the whole puz=
zle. =E2=80=9CIf you don=E2=80=99t involve these populations,=E2=80=9D he e=
xplained, =E2=80=9Cit doesn=E2=80=99t matter. If Africa isn=E2=80=99t plugg=
ed in, it doesn=E2=80=99t matter. If India isn=E2=80=99t plugged in, it doe=
sn=E2=80=99t matter.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Many of the credit-producing projects are located in the Global South =E2=
=80=93 farms in India, rainforests in Brazil, wildlife protection in Kenya,=
 etc=E2=80=A6 =E2=80=93 and importantly, rely on local people to protect an=
d verify. That work, paid for by developed countries, provides living wages=
 for local people while also protecting the environment. It=E2=80=99s beaut=
ifully connected =E2=80=93 environmental projects can create new tools and =
opportunities for financial inclusion as a byproduct.
It=E2=80=99s little connections like that that I think make people in the C=
elo ecosystem so excited. Once you start seeing the benefits of more connec=
ted and regenerative systems, you start seeing them everywhere.=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s a little intoxicating, and the energy in the community is infe=
ctious. I felt it in every conversation I had. Phil at Flowcarbon described=
 it perfectly, =E2=80=9CMy Celo Connect conference high hasn=E2=80=99t died=
 down since I got home. These are people who actually care and want to buil=
d systems that benefit everyone.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Mission matters, particularly to mission-driven builders.=C2=A0
Building a More Beautiful and Prosperous World
It should be clear at this point that I=E2=80=99m excited about what=E2=80=
=99s happening in the Celo ecosystem and that I=E2=80=99m unabashedly rooti=
ng for it to succeed, for my portfolio=E2=80=99s sake, sure, but also becau=
se I love the promise of regenerative financial models. If money is a story=
, and web3 is a chance to rewrite it, we should do so in a way that benefit=
s the planet.=C2=A0
There=E2=80=99s almost no trade-off: it would be better for stablecoins to =
be backed by assets that incentivize planet-positive behavior than to be ba=
cked by ponzi schemes.=C2=A0
That said, there are challenges to building on Celo, namely liquidity. If a=
 tree gets tokenized on a blockchain, and no one=E2=80=99s there to buy the=
 NFT, did it really get tokenized?=C2=A0
When I asked Ravi at Loam about the trade-offs, he admitted that =E2=80=9CI=
f you launch an NFT on Celo, you=E2=80=99ll get lower reach.=E2=80=9D But t=
hen he added, =E2=80=9CWe were excited about making an NFT, and then we ask=
ed ourselves why we were doing it and we didn=E2=80=99t have a good reason,=
 so we didn=E2=80=99t. That=E2=80=99s actually a benefit of a smaller commu=
nity: when the audience is small, you=E2=80=99re more intentional about wha=
t you do.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Certainly, the Ethereum, Solana, Polygon, and other ecosystems have more ac=
tive financial communities and deeper pools of capital buying assets than C=
elo does today. Other blockchains are able to offer projects greater financ=
ial incentives to build on them.=C2=A0=C2=A0
But through the $100 million DeFi For the People initiative [ https://email=
=2Emg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkMuOhSAMhp_msNM=
AguKCxWzmNQyXquRwMYAz8e2Ho4tJmvZvmuZ=
vP6MqbClf8kilok9a6nWAjPBbPNQKGZ0F8uKsJCMVA2czspJZIrhArixrBgjKeVnzCeg4tXdGVZ=
fivYEx5WiX88iHlYwjWDaPgmsmxkkYis0Meh4G9viq0zqIBiT8QL5SBOTlXutRXsPXi363CGDdG=
XqTQmsM-JTy1pTqgopuhVJTt6bcWVjdLeoO3QHp8NAxLZiaCbVcD8hJiinFjHJCucC4H3o2KqJX=
ReZVi0kp82I4bLQvpy5VmffHE2UZU9Upu7i18XtXAfw9aG8vrYYzunotEJX2YB8i9QF7M1o2iJA=
bcLuo2nByLGbSEibjQ6Ah43SiUzsONWeb2lb8N_0DmVuPsw ], Celo is partnering with =
DeFi blue chips like Curve, Sushiswap, and Aave. And on Friday, a governanc=
e proposal for a =E2=80=9Cgreen DEX=E2=80=9D [ https://email.mg2.substack.c=
om/c/eJxFkN2KhDAMhZ_GXkp_rD8XvVhY5jUkttEpo620cQbffjt6sZCeQEM4J58FwiWm0-wxE_=
vKSOeOJuAnr0iEiR0Z0-idEa3slW4G5kzjRK975vM4J8QN_GooHcj2Y1q9BfIxXBucS82eRsAkB=
ttYJ9sW1DxIkK0TA2oLjRg6dfvC4TwGiwbfmM4YkK3mSbTnSv1U8lEK9r0-gs8f2OuYlutTFX1H=
wtJkeaKt1MM-wYdK_ZZgISAxbySXkjdSC6l7zmtVNy2IaQYxzFPfAdiq4dsi63xMmcC-ahs3lky=
INMXkw1LGrydsuF6DcuZY-lay0DligGlFdxOgG-TFZFwwYCqA3QhU8GneD6IIF-19cUGkZSe7Eo=
4VZxe_gf9N_wDqiYkq ] went out to the Uniswap community. That would mean mor=
e global users for Uniswap, and more liquidity for green assets on Celo.=C2=
=A0
Beyond crypto liquidity, there are tens of billions of corporate, instituti=
onal, and individual dollars waiting on the sidelines to purchase and inves=
t in regenerative assets as soon as they can be produced and verified. The =
hard part was that, without the yield-seeking missiles that other blockchai=
n ecosystems have, that early liquidity was harder to come by on Celo, but =
it seems like we=E2=80=99ve reached a tipping point. Today, there=E2=80=99s=
 a vibrant early stage funding ecosystem with funds like Allegory and Flori=
, partnerships with blue chip DeFi protocols to provide liquidity once toke=
ns are created, and a standing bid from the Celo Reserve for quality natura=
l capital assets.=C2=A0
Ultimately, liquidity can be enticed to move, community and mission are imp=
ossible to fake. Plus, there=E2=80=99s something a little magical about a s=
mall but passionate community that=E2=80=99s built a movement out of the li=
melight. Building without the hype and yield farming and degens, focusing p=
urely on how to build a regenerative financial system in the real-world usi=
ng newly programmable money, feels more solid, more=E2=80=A6 sustainable.=
=C2=A0
In his recent Atlantic [ https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkUFuwyAQRU8Td=
rEwNsQsWHTTa1gDTGxUDBHgRu7pO04qVUIzXwxf8_Vw0HDJ5TCPXBs7y9yOB5qEzxqxNSxsr1jm=
4E2vxDTIUTNvRt9PcmKhzveCuEGIppUd2WO3MThoIaeXg3Mh2WpOo7dKTyjs6HqlBqWVHhTom9T=
TXb33wu4DJocGv7EcOSGLZm3tUS_Dx0V80nk-n11bEVqE1ILrXN7odoMFfkJCklDcGr5PJbgQ1L=
ikUrMLEK8b-gBXj1t2BdxxpcS1XS1YjPRICQqkSbBgTjMfheyFnDjvhm5U0Ns79PpupxuAu4x8W=
0RXd1sbuK8zCCsm5WZzCWmh8dcKG8bXgKDM1Lc9hXbMmMBG9G9e7Y39RXBeMGGh7_AzNIIt-aR7=
Krz_40NApbiJG4VjtNlncqX_pb8XtpiU ] essay [ https://email.mg2.substack.com/c=
/eJxFkUFuwyAQRU8TdrEwNsQsWHTTa1gDTGxUDBHgRu7pO04qVUIzXwxf8_Vw0HDJ5TCPXBs7y9=
yOB5qEzxqxNSxsr1jm4E2vxDTIUTNvRt9PcmKhzveCuEGIppUd2WO3MThoIaeXg3Mh2WpOo7dKT=
yjs6HqlBqWVHhTom9TTXb33wu4DJocGv7EcOSGLZm3tUS_Dx0V80nk-n11bEVqE1ILrXN7odoMF=
fkJCklDcGr5PJbgQ1LikUrMLEK8b-gBXj1t2BdxxpcS1XS1YjPRICQqkSbBgTjMfheyFnDjvhm5=
U0Ns79PpupxuAu4x8W0RXd1sbuK8zCCsm5WZzCWmh8dcKG8bXgKDM1Lc9hXbMmMBG9G9e7Y39RX=
BeMGGh7_AzNIIt-aR7Krz_40NApbiJG4VjtNlncqX_pb8XtpiU ], Jonathan Haidt wrote =
a line that I suspect I=E2=80=99ll be quoting often: =E2=80=9CThere is a di=
rection to history and it is toward cooperation at larger scales.=E2=80=9D =
I=E2=80=99ve written before that the crypto=E2=80=99s superpower is that it=
 can give digital assets physical properties with digital superpowers.=C2=
=A0
I think Celo=E2=80=99s magic might be providing the tools to recreate the c=
ooperation and trust of a local community on a global scale. When I asked E=
d Walters what city Celo is like, he called it a =E2=80=9Crobust, alive, vi=
brant neighborhood.=E2=80=9D Local environmental movements have felt a litt=
le like the Lorax =E2=80=93 incredibly well-intentioned, but lacking the to=
ols to make a real impact.=C2=A0
Celo, and the ReFi movement, might provide the tools to level the playing f=
ield by connecting the interests and contributions of people around the glo=
be, and by backing a new money with the things we want to see more of in th=
e world.=C2=A0
Money is just a technology, and today, people can program money to do all s=
orts of things, like align incentives across people, species, and time. And=
 technology is a story with wings, so let=E2=80=99s end with another story.=
=C2=A0
Kim Stanley Robinson=E2=80=99s The Ministry for the Future [ https://email.=
mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkMtuhDAMRb9msgMlgfBYZNHNbKpu2g9ADjFMNJCgxBTRr286LCpZ=
15IfuvYZgXAO8dRbSMT-ZKBzQ-3xSAsSYWR7wjg4q0Uju0rVPbO6tqJTHXNpmCLiCm7RFHdk224=
WNwK54F8bnEvFHrqfRjlxJRuoJttLAwL42NRC9LztGq4uX9itQz-ixm-MZ_DIFv0g2tKtervJe4=
7jOEpY4Sf4cgxrLnw47xLFs7jvtEcs3t1afBH4Bc_iMxjnU_B5zG5ZeCWainNRNcxpyaXktVRCq=
o7zsirrBoSZQPST6VqA8VbzdZZl2k0iGJ9_fixqH8iE6Pyc288HrLi8GvntIed1947OAT2YBe1F=
hC6wL0bDjB5jBm4HoIxT8a4XWbhoLgIZmZKtbPNxLDvbkLf8v-kvko6PXA ] =E2=80=93 a ne=
ar-future sci-fi novel that follows fictional characters as they experience=
, and try to deal with, the impacts of climate change =E2=80=93 is the grow=
nup version of The Lorax. It was one of Barack Obama=E2=80=99s favorite boo=
ks of 2020.=C2=A0
Since it=E2=80=99s the grownup version of The Lorax, The Ministry for the F=
uture doesn=E2=80=99t leave the planet=E2=80=99s survival up to a small, ta=
lkative little creature.=C2=A0
What the titular Ministry suggests instead is =E2=80=9Csome kind of carbon =
coin. This to be a digital currency, disbursed on proof of carbon sequestra=
tion to provide carrot as well as stick, thus enticing loose global capital=
 into virtuous actions on carbon burn reduction.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
In the sci-fi version, a decade into the future, when things are too far go=
ne for small actions, the carbon coin is =E2=80=9Cbacked by hundred-year bo=
nds with guaranteed rates of return, underwritten by all the central banks =
working together.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
The carbon coin is an answer to both the tragedy of the commons, and what t=
he book called =E2=80=9Cthe tragedy of the time horizon. Meaning we can=E2=
=80=99t imagine the suffering of the people of the future, so nothing much =
gets done on their behalf.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
In other words, the carbon coin is kind of like the SuperLorax =E2=80=93 it=
 speaks for the trees, the animals, and future generations, and it does mor=
e than speak: it creates a new financial system that accounts for all of th=
e interests that the old one, using older financial technology, couldn=E2=
=80=99t.=C2=A0
That=E2=80=99s the promise of Celo: that it gives people a set of tools wit=
h which, and an ecosystem within which, to build a new financial system tha=
t creates the conditions for prosperity for everyone by better accounting f=
or everyone=E2=80=99s debits and credits, extractions and contributions.=C2=
=A0
Celo doesn=E2=80=99t want to do it alone. It=E2=80=99s not going to be the =
blockchain to end all blockchains. It just wants to fulfill its own unique =
purpose as the mission-driven home neighborhood for ReFi within a connected=
, multi-chain ecosystem working together to create a regenerative economy.
I think this is how the financial system would have been built all along if=
 humans had had the right tools and technology. We do now. The goal is to b=
uild a new regenerative system before it=E2=80=99s too late.
Thanks to Rene, Ed, Tomer, Marek, Phil, Ravi, Mike, Anna, Sep, Jonathan, an=
d Deana for your conversations and contributions to this piece, and to Dan =
for editing.=20
Thanks for reading, and see you on Thursday,
Packy

